title: Snap-In Mendel Filament Guide, with diagonal slot

description.text: Many of the filament guides I've seen require either more vitamins (bolts/nuts/rods), or the removal of the frame nuts for installation. I had a heck of a time squaring and tightening my frame, so I didn't want to have to take it apart again. This filament guide is a snap-in one designed for the pitch of the threaded rods on the original Mendel (58.89mm). I don't know if the Prusa has a different pitch, but this guide should work even if it is up to about 5-7mm narrower than the Mendel (obviously wider won't work so well without modification). I printed one out of PLA and it snaps in nice and snug. ABS may have different stiffness. I also used the diagonal slot idea from fil's thing http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11222, but I moved it around to the top like he suggested so that the guide can be installed "either way".

Print, snap-in, install filament (or snap it in, too!). 
Skeinforge 35 was giving me STL errors about holes in the triangles, but it seemed to print ok. I have also included the native file (Solidworks) for editing.

comments.text:

After about 3 years of use, the y-axis motor holder in my Makerbot 2X cracked and broke into multiple pieces. My printer couldn't really control it's movement along the y-axis, and the quality of my prints was nonexistent. This was sad. I made a new piece on OpenSCAD, and printed it at school. 
IMPORTANT: PRINT THIS IN ABS PLASTIC (or something stronger)
I had originally printed this in PLA, but after about only half an hour of printing with it attached, the side touching the motor started to melt (for some reason the motor was at 130*C), and with the weight of the motor, it warped out of shape, and the prints started dying again. I swapped it out with one printed in ABS, and thus far it hasn't had that problem.

description.text: A candy dish, for when you have a brilliant idea. This is a remix of a model from Lincolnshire museum based on the original sculpture. (http://lincoln3dscans.co.uk/lowenthal-bust-one/). I hollowed it out and added the hinge to turn it into a candy dish. Those are mini m&ms in the bowl to give you an idea of scale. The hinge uses a piece of 1.75 mm filament as the hinge pin. For a finish I primed it and then applied a mix of real bronze powder and glue followed by a coat of varathane. The bronze had to be polished first. I'm sure it will look nice with just paint as well or leave it raw. This is my holiday gift to a number of friends and family. Maybe it will be yours too. There is a version on cults3d.com that has a much finer hinge that is not quite so ugly. It took some time to shrink it and get it right, hence the charge there.

My first moving thing. I'ts still ongoing. I created it as an experiment to see how effecient i could make it. The plan beeing is to make it self sufficient. So far i have failed to locate a rechargeable powersource around 5 volts that is small enough to make this a challenge. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sPEQ3l6myPA&feature=c4-overview&list=UUuw7dxgWVBNh-N-Q819tEfg It's an easy build containing:
2x 9g servos
1x Arduino Nano
4x 91 Ohm resistors
1x solarpanel
1x Soldering lab board
4x Light sensitive resistors
some cables
Glue gun All the pieces are easy to find online. If you need the code (fairly basic so far) it's in the files section. I included the CATparts if you want to scale this to fit other solarpanels and/or lab boards. It will probably work in any scale. Using steppers probably works just as good if you change the code an build a stepper driver..

Print the parts, screw the servos in place. I glued the solar panel in place and i did glue the "servo heads"(?) in the slots on their repective pieces.  
I also glued the light sensitive resistors in their places.  
"Sun resistors" creates a voltage divider between an anlog port and 5 volts and are coupled to ground using the other resistors.  
To follow the sun simply write a program that compares the voltages in each plane and moves the servos to minimize the difference.  
That is about as far as i have taken this right now. I also added code to prevent the panel to move i low light condition by messuring the avrage light over all four sensors and limiting movement over a specific value. Oh and i added som variables to find tune speed, position and so on...

title: Vortex/Smoke Ring Toys
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
These are a series of toy's for creating "smoke rings" or vortex rings using smoke, vapor, etc. that is inhaled then exhaled through the toy. This takes the guess work out of trying to figure out how to do it with your mouth and turns into quite a display, especially with the multiple ring versions.
First file produces one large ring, second file produces two smaller rings, third file produces four even smaller rings.
To make it work simply inhale some vapor or smoke put your mouth to the largest circular end and either exhale very slightly with a slight puff of air or raise your tongue to the roof of your mouth repeatedly. You can also tap your cheek very slightly to the same effect.
Scale to size desired, printing larger produces larger rings (easy), smaller creates smaller rings (harder).
More photos of it in action coming later, taking pictures of smoke rings is a pain. More designs to come.
Multipurpose: These can also be used to create bubbles.

Flashforge Creator Pro

Travel: 70mm/s The quad smoke ring version has a small support bracket that easily breaks off once printed directly inside the tube portion where your mouth goes.

description.text:
Inside (.stl files): Base
Stand
Archimedes screw (BTM, MID)
Pulley drive (slave)
Clips
Adjustment screws Here it is! The first release to the Goldberg Machine. We have started off with a 'simple' Archimedes screw. To make it more interesting and FUN, you can print as many segments as you like and make the Archimedes screw as LONG AS YOU WANT. It also has a stand with functioning angle adjustments to alter the incline of the Archimedes screw as you see fit. Archimedes screws are connected to 'ready to operate' pulley drive via rubber band or similar. Functioning Archimedes screw tested on small balls and liquids. Essential Parts: Base x1
Stand x1
Archimedes screw BTM x1
Pulley Drive x1
Adjustment screws x2 Extending: Archimedes screw MID x1
Clip x1 Print as many clips and Archimedes screw MID as desired to achieve desired length.
Crank, motor mount, pulley ratios for torque and top stabalising needle will be added this week, by FRIDAY 11:59pm. All stl. files have been tested at there current sizes. Layer height of 0.2mm with NO SUPPORT MATERIAL NEEDED on any files (You may need to slow down the bridging speeds for safer bridging). I have added some manual support on the Archimedes screws as images to follow will explain.
Glues or fixing agents are not necessary though will help performance. Lubricant around pulley 'slave drive' is recommended. Aside; Though the volume on the Screws are symmetrical around it's middle axis, the difference in top layers and wall thickness while 3D printing can cause the object weight to become very slightly off center. In very long Archimedes screws this difference may accumulate and become noticeable. These will eventually require the stabalising pin (to come). If you scale the Archimedes screw up by a factor of 2, scale the clips up also by a factor of approximately 2.05-2.1 to make up for the loss give. Clips are hard to put in and hold firmly, be careful when adding in sections. Please show your support by following EYN2K on social media.

description.text:
This is tool to coat a glass bed with ABS slurry. I use both gluestick and abs slurry for printing with ABS. The gluestick is for normal prints. If the print needs to have a very smooth and shiny bottom, I print on abs slurry. Sadly after every print the slurry coat need to be re-done. Coating the glass with a slurry is surprising simple:
  • Do a small amount of acetone on the clean! glass.
  • Use the abs spreader to spread out the acetone over the glass bed. This will dissolve a small amount of the spreader to coat the glass with.
    • Better remove the glass from the printer when coating it in case some of the acetone drops of the glass. A melted printer is not a good sight. The acetone will evaporate very fast, so after a couple of minutes you are left with a beautiful coated glass bed.
    Acetone is not very good for your health, so don't inhale to much. A syringe very useful to store and apply the acetone on the bed.They will not dissolve in acetone. Use a blunt needle or applicator tip. After using just but the lid back on and store the syringe upright. The acetone will not evaporate. The spreaders are stackable. Print out two spreaders. Then you can store the wet one on top of the other. Or print one for every color you need. The abs slurry on the glass forms the bottom layer of any prints. Therefore use ABS for the spreader that is not visible in the later print. So use either transparent ABS or use ABS in the same color as the where you going to print with.

Ich habe die Lautsprecherkabel für meine Heimkinoanlage in den Scheuerleisten verlegt. Um eine komfortable Anschlußmöglichkeit für die Bananas zu haben, habe ich diese kleinen Gehäuse entworfen. To have a comfortable connection option for Bananas, I have designed these small housing. In order to tighten the nuts inside, you need the special key (see photo), for another tool is not enough space!
So you can print without support, the holes for the sockets by a layer (0.3 mm) are closed filament, these can be easily removed after printing.

author: pedrop

title: Bow stabilizer - W/ carbon arrow shafts, shock absorber and customizable looks and weight

description.text:
A cool looking and easily built 30" rod This is especially done for the archery lovers out there. Greatly inspired by the Gau-19 gatling gun, here are some goals I set for the project:
  • Sexy looking: Works or not, you will have a neck-turner rod to show off at the range :P
  • Cheap, easy to print, easy to built. 3 carbon arrows, 2 bolts, a few nuts and a bit of PLA. Well under 20 bucks.
  • Functional: It must, to an extend, be able to flex, bend, absorb the shock of your shots and slow down the sight float. The triangular geometry and carbon shafts do an excellent job in this.
  • Customizable: Fits as many people, shooting styles and bows. You can print the 80mm or 100mm 7.5mm diameter short rods come in the file if you dont want to make a long rod at all or you dont have spare arrows.
  • And light as a breeze. Coz its made of plastic and carbon of course ;)
    • What you will need:
  • 3 Old arrow shafts (7.5mm) diameter of any length as the rod.
  • 1x UNF 5/16*24 2inch bolt, M8 washer and a nut. It goes into the stabilizer socket on most bows so, sadly, we have to comply with the Yanks' standards here.
  • 1x M10 90mm use as counter weight. Add as many nuts as you like to increase the weight.
  • Silicone glue. Strong, flexi, easy to clean and replaceable.
  • Black electrical tape
    • Some parts are novelty and aren't necessary to be printed at all.
    What you will get:
  • Stock: This houses the UNF bolt that connects to your bow
  • Brace: These pieces with keep the shafts from over bending and torquing. Print as many as you like.
  • Spring Coil: We don't have fancy rubber material here so I stick with good ol springs for shock absorber. Refer to my photos and hutch914's spring form customizer on how to build this part.
  • Barrel: This houses the springs, the M10 nuts and bolt and the whole thing acts as the shock absorber. Two springs, placed opposite each other, pre-compressed by the nut and bolt. The weight of the bolt, in turn, is suspended by the springs. The shock will be counter act by the bolt floating freely in the barrel chamber. I named this OSS (opposition suspension system) haha should I patent it ?
  • Muzzles: All muzzle caps are for show :) Tho the suppressor can be filled with cotton balls or something else. Perhaps it would work ?
    • Customizables:
  • Change springs winding and length to get your desired flex for the bolt.
  • Add, subtract nuts to change weight and fit your bow. I think the heavier the bow, the heavier weight you need to balance it out.
  • Cut your arrows or use other material (PVC, Aluminium pipes?) to change the rod length.
    • Review: I have test used the stabilizer outdoor. It adds a bit of wobble on draw. But aiming is great. Sight float is slow down especially when my arm got tired after many shots. Follow up is nice too. I have never owned a long rod so I can't tell any more about the difference.

Notes: PLA, 199/65C, taped bed. You only need to add a bit of support for the washer socket underneath the barrel. Tighten up your x-y belts! Some small tolerance goes down to .20mm. My Elcheapo 200euro reprap did an excellent job. Yours can too! It is wise to add mouse ears to prevent curling. I did! Parts will fit more nicely if there were no warp and curl.

Build: Use silicone glue, wrap a thin layer around both ends of the arrow. Ram the arrow into their slots. It will push out the glue and make a nice fat sealant ring. After an hour, the glue settles in and the stabilizer will be good to go. Use black tapes on two sides to pin down the braces. If the muzzle feels lose, place small stripes of tape to the inner side (tape should go over the corner). Fits very well! Silicone glue is strong but easy to pull out and clean. Good if you want to recycle the arrows for other projects. I have more to come :P Pin down braces with tapes Silicone rings form nicely The OSS OSS setup Add mouse ears to prevent curling. Go even cheaper! Split the short rod to half. Print them horizontally on bed. It will be very fast (9mins x 2) vs 1h30mins when printing the 100mm rod vertically and more importantly stronger. Glue the halves with wonder glue. Enjoy! 100mm short rod printable setup. No need arrows for shafts.
